"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882406","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-04-18","<p>The Department welcomes commercial investment in UK digital infrastructure such as Virgin Media’s Project Lightning and is working to encourage further investment through policies and funding. These include Business Rates Relief for fibre investment and the £200m Local Full Fibre Networks programme to fund locally-led projects that leverage commercial investment in full fibre broadband connections. For alternative network providers, £400 million of public funding has also been made available for fibre connectivity through the Digital Infrastructure Investment Fund, which will unlock approximately £1 billion of private investment.</p><p> </p><p>Looking further ahead, the Future Telecoms Infrastructure Review is currently assessing what market models can best support broadband infrastructure investment in different areas of the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s existing £1.7bn Broadband Delivery UK programme reached 95% of premises in December 2017 and is continuing with at least a further 2% likely to be achieved, ensuring that over 97% of premises in the UK can receive superfast broadband.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-04-18T15:23:23.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882406/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882406/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882406/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-04-13","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential merits of launching a new scheme, similar to Project Lightning, to ensure that more homes can provide usable broadband.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","135468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882407","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-23","<p>UKECP was founded in 2009 and is made up of Defra and Export Certification Ltd (ECL). The partnership reviews resources on a regular basis under their terms of agreement, to ensure that the financial and staffing arrangements in place are adequate to deliver our joint aspirations in beef market access. Last year Defra contributed £65,000 and ECL contributed £144,700 giving a total budget of £209,700. ECL consists of five directors one of whom is a vet. It can also draw upon the expertise of three additional vets and contractors.</p><p> </p><p>Industry has recently agreed to increase its financial contributions to the partnership by up to 20% and additional veterinary support has been taken on. In addition, six Defra policy and veterinary officials support the work of the partnership, with over 400 export health certificates for livestock products available to exporters.</p><p> </p><p>Export certifications are issued by a 40 strong team at APHA in Carlisle.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-04-23T16:44:57.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882407/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882407/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882407/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-04-13","UK Export Certification Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the (a) financial and (b) staffing resources of (i) the UK Export Certification Partnership and (ii) that Partnership's beef certification team.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","135469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882408","Treasury","false","2018-04-18","<p>In the “Estimated cost of minor tax reliefs” publication, figures are rounded to the nearest £5 million. Costs of less than £3 million are considered negligible for the figures used to answer Questions 130023, 130025, 130026, 130027, 130028, 130029 and 130030.</p><p> </p><p>The “Estimated cost of minor tax reliefs” publication can be accessed using the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/689452/Dec_17_Minor_Reliefs_Final_Revised.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/689452/Dec_17_Minor_Reliefs_Final_Revised.pdf</a></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-04-18T13:50:18.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882408/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882408/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882408/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-04-13","Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 5 March 2018 to Questions 130023, 130025, 130026, 130027, 130028, 130029 and 130030, what figure his Department uses for tax reliefs to estimate the cost to the Exchequer is negligible.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","135470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882409","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-18","<p>The sourcing and provision of hospital food and catering facilities to meet the standards for nutrition and hydration is a matter for local determination, as every hospital will have different local circumstances. Every hospital has a responsibility to provide the highest level of care possible for their patients and this includes the quality and nutritional value of the food that is served and eaten.</p><p> </p><p>It can be helpful for NHS trusts to use local, in-season ingredients where possible, to minimise energy used in food production, transport and storage, as well as supporting the local economy, thereby promoting local employment. The NHS Standard Contract for providers requires them to have regard to the ‘Government Buying Standards for Food and Catering Services.’</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-04-18T16:21:47.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882409/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882409/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882409/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-13","Hospitals: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the Government’s policy is on hospitals sourcing food that is produced locally.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","135471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882410","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-18","<p>The Department commissioned an evidence review from Public Health England on the public health burden of alcohol, which was published in 2016. This report was a comprehensive review of available evidence, which included the availability of alcohol and its impact on various socioeconomic groups. The report is available to view online at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/583047/alcohol_public_health_burden_evidence_review.pdf" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/583047/alcohol_public_health_burden_evidence_review.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government will continue to review what further evidence is required to understand the impact of minimum unit pricing to inform future policy decisions, drawing upon the expertise of Public Health England.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-04-18T16:02:50.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882410/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882410/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882410/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-13","Alcoholic Drinks: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what role Public Health England will play in monitoring the effect of the implementation of a minimum unit price for alcohol in Scotland to inform any decision on that policy in England.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","135472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882411","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-23","<p>The Department commissioned an evidence review from Public Health England (PHE) on the public health burden of alcohol, which was published in 2016. This report was a comprehensive review of available evidence, which included the availability of alcohol and its impact on various socioeconomic groups. The report is available to view online at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/583047/alcohol_public_health_burden_evidence_review.pdf" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/583047/alcohol_public_health_burden_evidence_review.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>No specific assessment has been made on the effect of the ban on below-cost sales of alcohol on alcohol-related hospital admissions since its introduction. However the PHE review estimated that the ban has prevented 14 deaths and 500 alcohol-related admissions to hospital per annum.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-04-23T16:20:11.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882411/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882411/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882411/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-13","Alcoholic Drinks: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the ban on below-cost sales of alcohol on alcohol-related hospital admissions since the introduction of that ban.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","135473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882412","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-23","<p>No such assessment has been made.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has made clear to NHS England that the Referral to Treatment standard, as described in The National Health Service Commissioning Board and Clinical Commissioning Groups (Responsibilities and Standing Rules) (Amendment) (No.2) Regulations 2015, is nothing less than the statutory standard.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-04-23T09:43:13.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882412/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882412/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882412/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-13","Hospitals: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department has made an assessment of or received legal advice on the implications for patients of non-compliance with part (9)(43)(3) of The National Health Service Commissioning Board and Clinical Commissioning Groups (Responsibilities and Standing Rules) Regulations 2012, which states that a relevant body must make arrangements to ensure that at the end of each data collection period not less than 92 per cent of the persons falling within paragraph 4 have been waiting to commence treatment for less than 18 weeks.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","135474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882413","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-18","<p>National depreciation budgets for all Government Departments are ring-fenced by HM Treasury and this means that underspends against that budget cannot be used for other types of spending. Therefore, any underspend (or overspend) against that budget will have no impact on National Health Service capital spending.</p><p> </p><p>Depreciation spending in NHS providers does not form part of the ring-fenced national depreciation budget and the Department does not set depreciation budgets for the NHS provider sector. Individual providers fund depreciation spending through income received from NHS commissioners in return for the provision of healthcare services.</p><p> </p><p>In terms of future NHS capital investment, the Autumn Budget 2017 announced £3.5 billion of new capital investment in the NHS by 2022-23, which comes on top of the £425 million of capital funding to support accident and emergency performance and to support locally-led sustainabilty transformation partnerships that was announced at the Spring Budget 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for ring-fenced national budgeted and outturn depreciation spending are shown in the following table.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Budget (£ million)</p></td><td><p>Outturn (£ million)</p></td><td><p>Under / Over spends (£ million)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>1,119</p></td><td><p>1,210</p></td><td><p>-90</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>1,141</p></td><td><p>1,193</p></td><td><p>-53</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>1,182</p></td><td><p>1,132</p></td><td><p>50</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>1,224</p></td><td><p>1,070</p></td><td><p>154</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>1,268</p></td><td><p>1,160</p></td><td><p>108</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>1,387</p></td><td><p>1,115</p></td><td><p>272</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>1,511</p></td><td><p>1,003</p></td><td><p>508</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>As depreciation spending in NHS providers does not form part of the ring-fenced depreciation budget, the under spends shown above will mostly relate to central Departmental budgets such as the centrally-managed informatics programme, NHS property services and impairments of stockpiled vaccines.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","135476","2018-04-18T16:24:49.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882413/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882413/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882413/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-13","NHS: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will make an assessment of the potential effect of recent underspending nationally on depreciation on (a) the NHS estate and (b) NHS equipment over the next (i) five, (ii) 10 and (iii) 15 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","135475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882414","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-18","<p>National depreciation budgets for all Government Departments are ring-fenced by HM Treasury and this means that underspends against that budget cannot be used for other types of spending. Therefore, any underspend (or overspend) against that budget will have no impact on National Health Service capital spending.</p><p> </p><p>Depreciation spending in NHS providers does not form part of the ring-fenced national depreciation budget and the Department does not set depreciation budgets for the NHS provider sector. Individual providers fund depreciation spending through income received from NHS commissioners in return for the provision of healthcare services.</p><p> </p><p>In terms of future NHS capital investment, the Autumn Budget 2017 announced £3.5 billion of new capital investment in the NHS by 2022-23, which comes on top of the £425 million of capital funding to support accident and emergency performance and to support locally-led sustainabilty transformation partnerships that was announced at the Spring Budget 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for ring-fenced national budgeted and outturn depreciation spending are shown in the following table.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Budget (£ million)</p></td><td><p>Outturn (£ million)</p></td><td><p>Under / Over spends (£ million)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>1,119</p></td><td><p>1,210</p></td><td><p>-90</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>1,141</p></td><td><p>1,193</p></td><td><p>-53</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>1,182</p></td><td><p>1,132</p></td><td><p>50</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>1,224</p></td><td><p>1,070</p></td><td><p>154</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>1,268</p></td><td><p>1,160</p></td><td><p>108</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>1,387</p></td><td><p>1,115</p></td><td><p>272</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>1,511</p></td><td><p>1,003</p></td><td><p>508</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>As depreciation spending in NHS providers does not form part of the ring-fenced depreciation budget, the under spends shown above will mostly relate to central Departmental budgets such as the centrally-managed informatics programme, NHS property services and impairments of stockpiled vaccines.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","135475","2018-04-18T16:24:49.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882414/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882414/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882414/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-13","NHS: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the variation between planned and actual spending on depreciation was nationally in each financial year since 2010-11; for what reason such variation occurred; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","135476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882415","Department for Education","false","2018-04-23","<p>In our ‘Unlocking Talent, Fulfilling Potential’ publication we set out our ambition to close the word gap in early years between disadvantaged children and their peers. This included actions to improve the quality of early years provision but did not include a commitment to increase early years practitioner numbers.</p><p> </p><p>The regulatory standards for registered providers caring for children from birth to five are set out in the Early Years Foundation Stage Statutory Framework, including the staff: child ratios and qualification levels for staff. It is a matter for private, voluntary and independent nurseries, as the employers of early year practitioners, to decide the staffing levels they wish to employ within the statutory guidelines.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-04-23T16:56:20.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882415/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882415/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882415/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-13","Pre-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to Unlocking Talent, Fulfilling Potential, what estimate he has made of the potential effect that increasing the number of early years practitioners in private, voluntary and independent nurseries will have on closing the early word gap.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","135477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882416","Department for Education","false","2018-04-23","<p>The Initial Teacher Training (ITT) Census publishes experimental statistics on the number of new entrants to Early Years ITT, including a breakdown by route. Data going back to academic year 2016/17 are available in the latest ITT Census publication, which is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/initial-teacher-training-trainee-number-census-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/initial-teacher-training-trainee-number-census-2017-to-2018</a>.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-04-23T16:57:48.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882416/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882416/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882416/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-13","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of recent trends in the number of people who enrol in early years teacher training.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","135478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882417","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-19","<p>The Foreign Secretary met Burmese State Counsellor Aung Sun Suu Kyi on 12 February and made clear that the Burmese authorities, including the military, must allow Rohingya refugees to return to their homes in Rakhine voluntarily, in safety and with dignity. The UK Ambassador to Burma met Minister for the Office of State Counsellor U Kyaw Tint Swe on 5 April and called on Burma to agree a Memorandum of Understanding that allows the UN High Commissioner for Refugees to monitor the returns process to ensure it meets international standards. The UK will use the UN Security Council’s visit to Burma and Bangladesh at the end of April to ensure the Burmese military recognises the international demand for safe, monitored and dignified refugee returns.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-04-19T15:10:07.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882417/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882417/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882417/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-13","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to encourage the Myanmar military to allow the safe, monitored and dignified return of the Rohingya people.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","135479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882418","Department for Education","false","2018-04-18","<p>The department will be working to develop the baseline assessment by trialling it in the 2018/19 academic year. A nationally representative selection of schools will be selected to participate in this trial, which will allow us to evaluate and refine the assessment. We will be consulting key stakeholders throughout this process.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-04-18T15:55:12.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882418/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882418/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882418/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-13","Pre-school Education: Assessments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when he plans to publish information on the tasks on which children will be assessed under the forthcoming early years baseline assessment; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","135480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882419","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-23","<p>We have committed in our 25 Year Environment Plan and Clean Growth Strategy to reforming our producer responsibility systems (including the packaging waste regulations) so that producers will take greater responsibility for the environmental impacts of their products.</p><p> </p><p>We plan to consult on these reforms alongside publication of the Resources and Waste Strategy later this year.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-04-23T11:12:05.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882419/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882419/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882419/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-04-13","Packaging: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether his Department plans to introduce changes to the Packaging Recovery Note system to strengthen producer responsibility before the publication of its Resources and Waste Strategy.","false","Biography information for Steve Double","St Austell and Newquay","Steve Double","135481"
